@node features "Features"

                               Features

-Easy installation: just run MeMonitor and use it!

-MeMonitor uses as little of the computer's ressources as possible,
 so you can run other applications, games, etc. at the same time.

-MeMonitor works on all Amigas with Workbench 2.0 or higher.

-When clicking on the @{" ? " link use} button, MeMonitor opens a new window
 which displays the current memory for each type (total memory,
 remaining memory and lowest amount of memory recorded since
 MeMonitor was activated), if you click on the '?' button when
 that window is already displayed, the amount of memory is updated
 to its current status.

@endnode

@node histo "History"

                               Versions History

  What follows are the various updates that were done since the first
version of MeMonitor.

1.0: -First public release.

2.0: -Bugfix: When the memory was below a certain level, the graph would
      not display correctly.
     -Now when MeMonitor's main window is resized under a certain size,
      only one graph will be shown, a @{" button " link use} will appear, so you can
      choose between the Chip or Fast memory graph.
     -A @{" ? " link use} button opens up a new window that displays the total memory
      the computer has, the current amount of memory and the lowest
      amount of memory recorded since MeMonitor was activated, this
      applys to both Chip and Fast memory.

2.01: -Unreleased test version.

2.02: -Bugfix: MeMonitor couldn't recognize any Fast memory exceeding
       32 megabytes (it thought there was no Fast memory at all).
      -If any type of memory is below 50 kilobytes, the graph is shown
       in red (or any colour used as colour 4 on the Workbench palette).
      -Now, clicking on the '?' button will update (or display, if it
       is not present) the window which shows the memory of your
       computer.

2.03: -Some internal code changes and various improvements were made.
      -Now if either memory is below 50K, MeMonitor displays 'Low Memory'
       in the appropriate graph window as well as the graph itself.

2.04: -Many small changes were made to the program code (simplification
       and/or enhancements made to some part of the code, especially for
       the graphs display).
      -Some cosmetic changes were made.

2.05: -The routine that displays both graphs has been revised. 
      -Some unneeded program code have been removed.
      -Various enhancements have been made to the program code.

@endnode

@node use "MeMonitor: Installation / usage"

                             Installation

  You can place MeMonitor anywhere you like (on your hard drive, Ram Disk,
etc.), or you can place it in the WBStartup drawer (although, depending on
your system, you may have to put a "Donotwait" in its tooltype).

  Note that MeMonitor needs at least Workbench 2.0 for it to run properly.

                         How to use MeMonitor?

  MeMonitor displays two graphs one for Graphic memory and the other for
the Fast (or 'Other') memory. The graphic display is updated every second
and each graph moves to the left by one pixel. If there is no Fast memory,
"No FastMem" will be written in its respective graph.

  Each of the graphs has fuel-gauge-like symbols (F, 1/2 and 0), so you
can have a good idea of how much memory your computer is using (or if you
prefer, how much memory is remaining :)

  You can resize it's window and MeMonitor will redraw the graphs
according to the new window size. Depending on how the window is resized,
the graphs will be drawn either side by side or one on top of the other
one, this is handy when you want to resize the window in such a way to
'uncover' some parts of the Workbench screen, but still want to see both
graphs at the same time.

  Sometimes you may want to reduce the window size to a minimum where
only one graph is shown at a time, an additionnal @{b}'Fast'@{ub} or @{b}'Chip'@{ub}
button appears (depending on which graph is currently shown, as the
label on it will always be for the other graph) and clicking on it
toggles between the Graphic Memory and Fast Memory graphs. If your
computer has no Fast memory, that button will not show.

  A button with a @{b}'?'@{ub} symbol is located on the lower left of the
window, clicking on it displays a new window where the following
information is shown:

   -Graphic Memory-

@{b}Total@{ub}:     The total Graphic memory available in your computer.
@{b}Available@{ub}: The current available memory.
@{b}Lowest@{ub}:    The LOWEST amount of memory recorded by MeMonitor.

   -Fast Memory-

@{b}Total@{ub}:     The total Fast (or 'Other') memory available.
@{b}Available@{ub}: The current available memory.
@{b}Lowest@{ub}:    The LOWEST amount of memory recorded by MeMonitor.

  You can click anytime you wish on the @{b}'?'@{ub} button, if the window
displaying the above information is present, the informations are
redisplayed and are updated if one or more of the memory status have
been changed.

  Note that if the Chip memory is below 10K, clicking on the '?' button
will have no effect, unless its current window is already displayed.

  Please note that the amount of graphic memory is taken from the
internal circuitry of your computer (the type of Agnus chip and its
related memory). If your Amiga has a graphic card, the graphic card's
memory is ignored.

@endnode

